importantDates.descriptionOfWhyDateIsRelevant: The date of the news article, indicating a recent college football game result and its impact on rankings and team performance.

importantTimeframes.descriptionOfWhyTimeFrameIsRelevant: The game occurred on this date, marking a pivotal moment in the Southeastern Conference football season for Missouri and Auburn.

keyTakeAways: Missouri defeated Auburn 23-17 in a dramatic overtime game, marking their first road win of the season and improving to 6-1, 2-1 in the SEC.
Beau Pribula scored on a 3-yard run in the second overtime and contributed 252 passing yards and two interceptions.
Ahmad Hardy rushed for 58 yards and two touchdowns, including a game-tying run with 5:07 left in regulation.
Auburn, now 3-4, 0-4 in conference play, struggled offensively, with Jackson Arnold throwing for 207 yards and one interception.
Auburn’s defense held Missouri to 10 points after the opening drive, but failed to score in the second half.
Missouri’s defense made a key fourth-down stop in overtime to seal the win, demonstrating resilience and discipline.
Hugh Freeze, Auburn’s coach, is 5-15 in SEC games and has a losing record at Jordan-Hare Stadium; his team is 1-19 in last 20 matchups vs. ranked opponents.
Missouri’s win boosts their chances of moving up in the AP Top 25 college football poll.
Auburn remains without a conference win and continues to face challenges in offensive production and consistency.
The game highlights ongoing struggles for Auburn’s offense under Freeze and the resilience of Missouri’s defense and execution.

summaryOfNewsArticle: In a dramatic overtime game on October 19, 2025, No. 16 Missouri defeated Auburn 23-17, marking their first road win of the season and improving to 6-1, 2-1 in the SEC. The victory was powered by Beau Pribula’s 3-yard run in the second overtime and Ahmad Hardy’s 58-yard rushing performance, including a game-tying run late in regulation. Missouri’s defense held Auburn to just 10 points after the opening drive and made a crucial fourth-down stop in overtime to seal the win. Auburn, now 3-4, 0-4 in conference play, continued its offensive struggles, with quarterback Jackson Arnold throwing for 207 yards and one interception, while the team remains without a win in conference play. Coach Hugh Freeze, who is 5-15 in SEC games and 1-19 in his last 20 matchups against ranked opponents, faces ongoing challenges in turning around the team’s performance. The win boosts Missouri’s chances of moving up in the AP Top 25 poll, while Auburn continues to search for its first conference win.
title: Missouri Defeats Auburn in Overtime to Improve to 6-1, 2-1 in SEC
